America of Two Kinds
New York — As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting the votes from the 2020 presidential election.
Once the results are finalized, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is to be expected in this highly competitive election with record voter turnout.
Only American citizens can vote for the president, but this choice affects people everywhere.
If it's too early to determine the election results, it's not too early to reflect on the implications of this election for the world's most powerful nation.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democracy.
Despite practical restrictions related to the pandemic, voter turnout remains high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And violent incidents are rare.
The courts are investigating decisions by the U.S. Postal Service that appear to be motivated by political considerations, hindering the delivery of ballots from regions where the majority of votes are expected to come from Democratic voters.
U.S. President Donald Trump made an unfounded announcement of victory on Tuesday night, which received little response, and his request to stop counting votes (at least in states where he was leading) seemed to be ignored.
However, it is concerning that the division among American voters remains significant.
The votes of the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a split in the government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will retain control of the Senate.
Governorships and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republicans having a slight edge).
The Democratic Party's expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a large margin, securing approximately four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This outcome did not come from strong authorization, nor does it stem from political adjustments.
Trump's polls were very strong, with 5 million more votes than in 2016, making it the second-highest vote count in U.S. presidential history and exceeding any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily new coronavirus cases and over 1,000 deaths.
Just as the consequences of his administration's mishandling of the pandemic became most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have significant influence, especially if he remains in the public eye (which also seems possible).
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of President George W. Bush or Ronald Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern form of American populism — will remain a powerful force.
It is no surprise that, despite having no evidence to back it up, Trump is striving to appear noble and upright, trying to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accusing there of voter fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is likely never to admit defeat, let alone attend the inauguration of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never encountered a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They sort themselves into different communities and regions based on shared views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civic curriculum has provided convenience for the differentiation among people from different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that national divisions are not usually along economic lines.
People from all classes voted for both candidates, and voting patterns based on population, gender, and race are not as one-sided as many predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the remedies.
Education level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographic location. Republican voters tend to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democrats tend to reside in metropolitan areas.
However, culture may play a bigger role in American politics than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seems not to be very important in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In this context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms such as the way presidential elections are conducted or how the government operates.
This situation is similar to the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representativeness, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is not surprising that those who would suffer losses from change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This largely depends on Mitch McConnell, the Republican Senate leader, and his willingness and ability to cooperate with the future Biden administration.
Collaboration also requires Biden to make compromises, which will certainly face resistance from ideologically strong members within his own party.
Democrats have tried to sharply reject everything that Trump and his representatives stood for.
But they failed.
Republicans were seeking an election that would recognize Trump.
But that did not happen as they wished.
Instead, the election revealed a nation divided into two groups of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
